    {
      "id": 40,
      "type": "Note",
      "pos": [
        -1201.696914,
        -125.66470800000039
      ],
      "size": [
        360.58551402553394,
        1018.0093120766019
      ],
      "flags": {},
      "order": 10,
      "mode": 0,
      "inputs": [],
      "outputs": [],
      "properties": {},
      "widgets_values": [
        "cfz-start :\nhelps with clearing terminal if you want, also if add it to other nodes, it will calculate how much time has passed between any two node or the full workflow. Finally can enable/disable cudnn.IF USING THIS WF WITH ZLUDA MAKE SURE TO DISABLE CUDNN ON THIS NODE.\n\nresolution :\nthe number entered is applied to both height and width of input image and resized (multiples of 16, better for wan), or can use any resolution manually of course (always make sure multiples of 16)\n\nlength : \nltx 2.3 can do 10 seconds or more, the example is 13 seconds for example. (24x13+1) , of course it can also do 25 fps, 30 or even 50-60 fps. Calculate accordingly.\n\ntotal steps / half-step :\nit divides total steps across high and low models, and you could change the half-step , it is not always the best for equal steps, so for example I sometimes use 3+1 , 1+1 , 3+2 ... etc.\n\nprompt & negative :\nthese are made with my cfz-caching nodes. You can of course use the usual clip loader-clip text encode way for both positive and negative, but if you do lots of gens with same prompt or at least use the same negative , you can create it and save it with the group named -prompt creation- and then refresh the window so you can see it on the \"prompt\" or \"negative\". To just run and generate and save prompts in that group, fill the text encode, give it a name in save conditioning and \"execute\" the preview as text node. This will let you generate prompts again and again and later use them on the workflow. AND all of this means you don't need to spend additional vram, system ram or time to use the clip model. (This is much important in ltx because clip is heavier on vram and gpu)\n\n*** I used cudnn toggle before vae's here, audio certainly is better without cudnn and if you use spatio tiled, with or without cudnn doesn't matter much.\n"
      ],
      "color": "#432",
      "bgcolor": "#653"
    },
